==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Abbot
<hw>Ab"bot</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧b"b⟦ucr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>abbod</ets>, <ets>abbad</ets>, L. <ets>abbas</ets>,
<ets>abbatis</ets>, Gr. <grk>'abba^s</grk>, fr. Syriac
<ets>abb⟦amac⟧</ets> father. Cf. <er>Abba</er>,
<er>Abb⟦eacute⟧</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The superior or head of an
abbey.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of a class of bishops whose sees were formerly
abbeys.</def> <rj><au>Encyc. Brit.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Abbot of the people</b></col>. <cd>a title formerly given
to one of the chief magistrates in Genoa.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Abbot of
Misrule</b></col> (or <col><b>Lord of Misrule</b></col>)</mcol>, <cd>in
medi⟦ae⟧val times, the master of revels, as at Christmas; in Scotland
called the <er>Abbot of Unreason</er>.</cd> <rj><au>Encyc.
Brit.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Abbotship</ent>⟦br⟧
